<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Bigot, 1882" authorityName="Moran &amp; Skevington" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Giglio-Tos" baseAuthorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Romaleosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Romaleosyrphus arctophiloides" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arctophiloides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Romaleosyrphus arctophiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only known member of 
<taxonomicName authority="Bigot, 1882" authorityName="Bigot" authorityYear="1882" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Romaleosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Romaleosyrphus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Romaleosyrphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in which the hind trochanter is not tuberculate in the male. Although males are not known for 
<taxonomicName authority="Bigot, 1882" authorityName="Moran" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Romaleosyrphus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Romaleosyrphus argosi" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argosi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Romaleosyrphus argosi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. drysus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="drysus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">R. drysus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. and 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. woodi" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="woodi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">R. woodi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., males of their closest relative in the COI gene tree, 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. nephelaeus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nephelaeus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">R. nephelaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., possess a tuberculate hind trochanter. It is therefore expected that males of these three species also have a tuberculate hind trochanter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
We suspect that a single specimen 
<normalizedToken originalValue="âCNC_Diptera142464â">&quot;CNC_Diptera142464&quot;</normalizedToken>
collected in the Sierra Madre Occidental may represent a distinct species from specimens collected in the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt pine-oak forests. Although no genital or discrete morphological differences could be found, the legs of this specimens are fully black pilose while those of all the others have a streak of yellow pile at the base of the fore and mid femora. Unfortunately, while a barcode was obtained for this specimen, no barcode sequences were obtained from specimens from specimens collected in the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt pine-oak forests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
